<HEAD>Seven Die in Social Club Basement Blaze</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Deletes outdated 4th graf `Traces of...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY48, NY53</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MEG THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fire gutted a packed <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION> social club Sunday afternoon, killing seven people and injuring more than 30, and firefighters' efforts were hampered by screaming people trying to get to relatives, authorities said. `` It was sheer panic,'' said firefighter <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Fennell </PERSON>. The inside of the basement club was burned out and `` it looked like people tried to claw out all of the walls,'' he said. Fire marshals were testing for the presence of flammable liquids, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulligan </PERSON>, a spokesman for the Fire Department. The origin was considered suspicious because of the fire spread so quickly, he said. The streets were filled with screaming people who tried to pull equipment from firefighters and get to their friends, <PERSON> Fennell </PERSON> said. `` There were people running around crazy ...,'' said firefighter <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Kisonas </PERSON>. `` When we went to go do our job, people were trying to fight the tools away from us. It was crazy. They wanted to pull us one way and then another way trying to get us to the people trapped in the basement.'' Firefighters said five bodies were found in the club, some still in chairs. Another person died shortly after the fire at a hospital and the seventh died about eight hours later at <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital-Cornell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, a spokeswoman said. Most of the injured, including six firefighters and two <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> technicians, were suffering from smoke inhalation and were taken to hospitals. <PERSON> Mulligan </PERSON> described the club as about 50 feet by 75 feet with 7-foot ceilings. Between 60 and 100 people were packed inside. Mayor <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON>, who toured the blaze aftermath, described the club as a `` rabbit warren.'' `` If people were running for their lives, they'd run down blind alleys and be trapped,'' said <PERSON> Koch </PERSON>, who described the space as confined and made up of small, partitioned cubicles. `` It's clear that it should have never been opened in the first place,'' he said of the club. <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Burns </PERSON>, a deputy fire chief, said the private bar known to neighbors as `` the hole'' was illegal because bars in basements are prohibited and the exits were inadequate. A resident of the area, <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Govia </PERSON>, 25, said the club operated 24 hours a day. `` Police often raided the place,'' he said. Authorities said they have trouble keeping illegal clubs closed because there are hundreds in the city. The fire was reported about 12:30 p.m. and firefighters were `` met by hysterical civilians streaming up the staircase,'' <PERSON> Mulligan </PERSON> said. `` One firefighter told me he literally had to fight his way down the stairs,'' <PERSON> Mulligan </PERSON> said. Most escaped through the club's front door and narrow staircase, but others were able to break through a wall near the back. A second door on the side of the club was locked, <PERSON> Mulligan </PERSON> said. Eighteen engine companies, nine ladder units and about 150 firefighters brought the five-alarm blaze under control about 3:15 p.m., <PERSON> Mulligan </PERSON> said.
