<SECOND>PM-Sudan-Floods,0898</SECOND>
<HEAD>Flood Victims Still Isolated, Unaided</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIDRIKKE SCHANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Omar </PERSON> <PERSON> Abakr </PERSON> <PERSON> Idris </PERSON> removes his shoes before wading through the knee-deep fetid water left behind by the worst rains on record in this desert capital. Each step across what used to be a dusty dirt road unleashes an overpowering stench. The vast expanse of water is contaminated with excrement from overflowing pit latrines and from dogs, goats and donkeys living in the village. <PERSON> Idris </PERSON>' village of <LOCATION> Mayo </LOCATION>, a shantytown of about 50,000 on <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION>'s southeastern fringe, was among the areas hardest hit by the deluge Aug. 4-5. `` We are struggling with life here now,'' said <PERSON> Idris </PERSON>, 48. `` We are without water, without food, without homes, without transport, without anything.'' The storm dumped 8.4 inches of rain in 14 hours, six times the amount that fell in all of 1987. For the past 30 years, annual rainfall has not exceeded 4.3 inches. At least 58 people died, most as their mud huts collapsed on them. Up to 1.5 million people _ more than a third of <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION>'s nearly 4 million inhabitants _ were left homeless and more than 150,000 dwellings were destroyed, according to government figures Most vulnerable were the people living in <LOCATION> Mayo </LOCATION> and 22 other squatter camps around <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION>. The illegal settlements hold 500,000 to 700,000 people who fled <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>'s southern civil war and widespread drought. The vast camps of mud huts and burlap-covered shacks are desperately poor and occupy the worst land. The Moslem-dominated government, at war with the Christian and animist south, long has tried to discourage further settlement in the squatter areas. It denies the areas any social services and forbids the displaced people living there from digging wells. Official neglect threatened to leave most of the displaced people beyond the reach of international relief after the storm. The government initially refused aid but ultimately relented in the face of the sheer magnitude of the disaster and the threat of epidemics sweeping from the camps. Many relief workers still worry the unplanned areas will receive less than their fair share of government aid. `` There will be a natural built-in bias towards planned areas,'' said <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> <PERSON> Wannop </PERSON>, resident representative of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> development program which is helping coordinate non-government relief. Emergency aid has yet to reach most of those affected by the flood, many of whom live in areas isolated by stagnant lakes which have nowhere to drain. Nearly all the mud huts in <LOCATION> Marzuk </LOCATION>, an unplanned area of about 15,000 people in <LOCATION> Omdurman </LOCATION> across the Nile river from <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION>, were destroyed or damaged by the rains. The people said they needed plastic sheeting and tents. `` They are very important because the children now are sleeping outside,'' said <PERSON> Abdullahim </PERSON> <PERSON> Kody </PERSON>, a resident. `` Once I had two rooms,'' <PERSON> Kody </PERSON> said, pointing to a mound of hardening mud. `` Unfortunately, they have fallen down.'' <PERSON> Kody </PERSON>, <PERSON> Idris </PERSON> and others interviewed nearly two weeks after the disaster said they received no help from anyone and were desperately in need of food, shelter, and medicine. Health officials are predicitng deadly epidemics of water-borne diseases as people cut off from drinking water supplies are forced to drink from the pools left behind by the rainstorm. Thousands already have developed diarrhea. Malaria and typhoid also are on the rise, and cholera is an imminent risk. Dr. <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>, a world health organization expert on diarrheal diseases an immunization, predicted 400,000 people, mostly children, will get sick and at least 4,000 will die. Without treatment, as many as 40,000 will perish, <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> estimated. But he said emergency health clinics established in response to the disaster should forestall the worst. Diarrhea kills the young and the weak primarily through dehydration and is treatable with a simple rehydrating mixture of salt, sugar and water. But lack of fresh water supplies make even this basic therapy difficult. Sudanese authorities blame insufficient supplies for delays in granting relief. More than 2,000 tons of tents, blankets, medicine, plastic sheeting, food and other items have poured into <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>, but officials have said it is about a tenth of what is needed. Disorganization and the dilapidated infrastructure of this North African nation of 23 million also have hampererd the relief operation. The rains knocked out telephones, disrupting coordination between the army-run operation and non-governmental agencies. The downpour also created mud bogs of roads already strewn with potholes from years of neglect. Another threat comes from the swollen <LOCATION> Nile </LOCATION> <LOCATION> river </LOCATION>, which already has swamped some island villages and is brimming near street level in the capital. Officials are not sure when or whether the river might overflow into the city. A pair of British cartographers working with government surveyors has begun work on a contour map which will help determine how much higher the Nile would have to rise before spilling into <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION>'s streets. In the meantime, relief efforts will continue. And people like <PERSON> Osman </PERSON> <PERSON> Geragandi </PERSON> <PERSON> Koko </PERSON>, who lives in a settlement built on a garbage pile in north <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION>, will do what they must to find food and shelter. `` Previously there was drought and we got through that,'' he said. `` We hope to get through this too.''
</TEXT>
