<HEAD>Two American Activists Arrested In South Korea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two American activists who addressed a student rally last week were arrested and ordered expelled for taking part in radical political meetings, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> said today. The two were identified as <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON>, 31, a secretary in the history department at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maryland </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Scheiner </PERSON>, 37, a <LOCATION> White </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, computer salesman. A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> consular officer said Ms. <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON> and <PERSON> Scheiner </PERSON> were arrested late Saturday leaving a meeting with other activitists. Both had tourist visas that prohibited them from any political activity, said a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official who spoke on condition of anonymity. The two were held overnight by <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> Immigration authorities and ordered to leave the country `` for activities inconsistent with their visa status.'' There were no available flights Sunday, so <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said the two spent Sunday night at the airport and would leave today. Both Ms. <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON> and <PERSON> Scheiner </PERSON> spoke to a rally at <ORGANIZATION> Yonsei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> Aug. 15 for some 3,000 students assembled to march to the border truce site of <LOCATION> Panmunjom </LOCATION> for talks with North Korean student delegates on reuniting the divided <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> peninsula. The government banned the march and riot police arrested 200 students. The Americans said they were here at the invitation of the <ORGANIZATION> Korean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> to attend an international peace conference. Ms. <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON> said that she represented the People's <ORGANIZATION> Anti-War </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mobilization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> based in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, which she described as `` a guerilla movement which wants the government to spend money on social causes, not defense.'' <PERSON> Scheiner </PERSON> said he represented a group called <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mobilization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Survival </ORGANIZATION> which wanted <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military forces pulled out of all foreign nations.
