<HEAD>Small Mexican Town Still Source Of Illegal Aliens In United States</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA MARIA DEL ORO, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When the new <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> immigration law went into effect last year, this town in <LOCATION> Durango </LOCATION> cattle country 500 miles south of <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paso </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, feared for its future. For nearly half a century, it had supplied Mexicans who worked legally or illegally in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and sent home the dollars that helped keep the town going. But the catastrophe <ORGANIZATION> Santa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maria </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> del </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oro </ORGANIZATION> braced for 14 months ago has n't happened. Thousands of dollars still pour in every day, in money orders sent by residents' relatives working, most of them illegally, in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Mayor <PERSON> Epifanio </PERSON> <PERSON> Carreon </PERSON> had feared the flow of dollars would dry up and, worse, hundreds of young men would come home looking for jobs that do n't exist. `` We would have seen at least some economic affects of the law by now, but everything is totally normal,'' <PERSON> Carreon </PERSON> says now. `` The dollar continues being the most important source of income in this region,'' said <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Acosta </PERSON>, assistant manager of <ORGANIZATION> Banco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Internacional </ORGANIZATION>, the only bank in the area people that cashes dollar checks. `` Some people returned because of fear before they knew what was going to happen with the law. But now things are back to normal.'' One young man in town said, however, he's waiting to see what happens with the law _ the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Immigration Control and Reform Act _ before he attempts his first crossing. `` If it were n't for the law I'd already be in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Rocky </PERSON> <PERSON> Rocha </PERSON>, 18, who just graduated from a technical school here. He said two of his brothers already there had applied for amnesty under the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> law and fear they'll lose out if they harbor him as an illegal alien. `` If my brothers will let me, I'll go in spite of the law,'' said <PERSON> Rocha </PERSON>. `` Here you work so hard and you do n't make much.'' <PERSON> Santa </PERSON> <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> del </PERSON> <PERSON> Oro </PERSON> has supplied the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> labor market with a steady stream of workers since World War II. Many residents went to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> as farm workers under the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bracero program of 1942, said Mayor <PERSON> Carreon </PERSON>. By now, some have gained <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizenship or legal residency. By the time the program was dropped in 1964, many local residents had grown accustomed to having a steady job and earning dollars. Besides, said <PERSON> Carreon </PERSON>, the local gold and mining operations were winding down and there was n't much left to do here but work in the fields or raise cattle. The only major employer around these days is a lumber company, which has about 300 workers. <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Angel </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON>, the municipal clerk, estimates that more than 30 percent of the town's 14,000 people still go back and forth to jobs in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Authorities estimate the percentage of people on surrounding farms and ranches with relatives working in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is as high or even higher. <PERSON> Carreon </PERSON> said the steady flow of dollars _ as much as $ 60,000 a week _ has helped <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Maria </LOCATION> <LOCATION> del </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Oro </LOCATION> weather <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s 6-year-old economic crisis. Indeed, by Mexican standards <PERSON> Santa </PERSON> <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> del </PERSON> <PERSON> Oro </PERSON> is well off. The main streets are filled with late-model <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Mexican pickup trucks, many bearing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> license plates. There are no beggars on the streets. Many of the homes and businesses were financed with dollars. Residents and public officials here say the law has helped those who hve been in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for a long time and wanted to stay there. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON> returned several years ago and bought a butcher shop with the money he earned as an undocumented worker in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. His brother, a <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> butcher, stayed and has applied for amnesty, the provision of the law allowing foreigners who meet certain requirements to seek legal residency. `` He feels a lot safer knowing that when he leaves the house -LRB- in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> -RRB- he'll return,'' <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON> said. Illegal aliens caught in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> most often are deported immediately. For others who did n't qualify for amnesty under the law or just did n't bother to apply, it's business as usual: a sundown trek across the border. `` We'll stay as long as there's work. When there's not we'll come back crying,'' said <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON>, 29, who has worked in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> as an undocumented worker for a decade `` Right now the work is there waiting for us,'' said <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON>, one of three brothers working without documents at a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> construction company. <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON>, home on vacation, said the $ 21 an hour he earns makes the risk of crossing as an illegal alien worthwhile. Similar work in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> probably would pay him about $ 12 a day. `` Right now it -LRB- the law -RRB- has n't affected us at all,'' said <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON>' 18-year-old brother who began working illegally in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> when he was 14. The toughest provision of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> law went into effect this past June 1, making it illegal for most employers to knowingly hire undocumented workers. The law calls for stiff fines and even jail sentences for violators. Agricultural workers now in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> have been given an extension to Dec. 1 to get their papers in order or leave. Although crossing the border without legal documents is the risky part, those who've worked in the same job in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> since before 1982 do n't have to show employers their documents.
