<FIRST>r i PM-Gulf-Analysis     08-21 0859</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gulf-Analysis,0886</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran And Iraq Count Cost Of Eight-Year War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As the smoke clears in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> war with a U.N.-sponsored truce, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> are counting the cost of a conflict that killed an estimated 1 million people but ended with no victor. Peace talks scheduled to start Thursday in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> are likely to be long and tough. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> are ancient enemies, and eight years of war have only deepened old hatreds. Both countries, bled by the war, face mammoth tasks in rebuilding their economies despite the oil wealth they used to bankroll their military machines. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> also faces the prospect of political turmoil as hardliners such as Interior Minister <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Akbar </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohtashemi </PERSON>, a vociferous critic of `` defeatist'' diplomatic efforts to end the war; and more pragmatic leaders, particularly Parliament Speaker <PERSON> Hashemi </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, battle for supremacy. <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, considered the most powerful figure in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> after <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>, is widely seen as the man who engineered <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>'s unconditional acceptance of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> cease-fire resolution last month when he realized <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s military machine was weakening after a string of battlefield defeats this year. <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> endorsed <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>'s decision, widely seen as the speaker's biggest political gamble, although the ailing patriarch stressed that for him, ending the war was `` worse than drinking poison.'' So far, no senior <LOCATION> Iranian </LOCATION> leader has publicly challenged that decision, which most Iranians have welcomed after eight years of appalling human loss. But <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, who also has made clear he seeks to end <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s isolation, faces an increasingly strong array of radicals led by <PERSON> Mohtashemi </PERSON> and the prosecutor-general, <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Khoeinihia </PERSON>, leader of the militants who seized the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> in November 1979, who oppose his pragmatist policies They consider his efforts to end a war he clearly believed <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> could never win flies in the face of the revolution's aim of spreading Islamic fundamentalism. Analysts say the internal struggle for supremacy after <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>, which has been swelling over the last two years as the patriarch's health deteriorated, has only been intensified by <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>'s acceptance of the On the ground, the two belligerents wound up virtually where they started in September 1980, when <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> invaded <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, the map unchanged after one of the longest conventional wars this century. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s President <PERSON> Saddam </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>, whose 1980 invasion is seen by military analysts a major blunder, has emerged at least for now more solidly entrenched in power in <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, which spent as much as $ 10 billion a year on its war effort, is as much as $ 85 billion in debt, according to Western economists. That makes it one of the world's biggest debtor nations. The war cost <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> an estimated $ 400 billion. Although it still has about $ 5 billion in foreign reserves, its economy is in tatters, its industry, particularly its oil installations, pounded by <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s powerful air force. <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>, whose hatred of <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> turned the war into a bloody vendetta, remains the unchallenged authority in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. But his surprise decision last month to accept the cease-fire, despite his exhortations to `` fight to the last drop of blood'' to topple the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> leader, has dented the 88-year-old religious patriarch's credibility. The Iraqis, armed with superior weaponry and technology, won something simply by surviving <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s human-wave offensives and wearing down the numerically superior Iranians, although <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> used outlawed chemical weapons and hammered <LOCATION> Iranian </LOCATION> cities with bombers and missiles. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, virtually friendless and starved of the arsenal of high-tech weaponry the Iraqis employed, can claim that it repelled the invaders and fought them to a standstill. The war undoubtedly helped cement <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s 1979 Islamic revolution. Opponents of the cleric-dominated <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> regime charge that the fundamentalists deliberately perpetuated the conflict to consolidate the infant republic and <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s stern brand of Islam. With an end to the war now a possibility, the Arab countries of the oil-rich gulf who were caught in the crossfire, and the rest of the Moslem world, are heaving a collective sigh of relief. But an end to the war will have strategic repercussions far beyond the gulf. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> fears that <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, which has participated to some extent in every Arab-Israeli war over the last four decades, eventually will turn its combat-hardened military machine again on the Jewish state. Defense Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> said last month that although he did not see any danger of an imminent <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> attack, the military buildup by <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> states spawned by the gulf war could be used against <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. With the gulf war out of the way, the <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> states are expected to refocus their attention on efforts to solve the older <LOCATION> Arab-Israeli </LOCATION> conflict. If <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> and his supporters, such as Foreign Minister <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Akbar </PERSON> <PERSON> Velayati </PERSON>, succeed in out-maneuvering their hard-line opponents in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s relations with the West are likely to improve. That, in turn, has raised hopes that <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> can be persuaded to use its influence with pro-Iranian Shiite extremists in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> to free foreign hostages, including nine Americans.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Blanche </PERSON>, based in <LOCATION> Nicosia </LOCATION>, is The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>' Middle East news editor.
