<HEAD>Five Years After Assassination, Doubts Remain</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Five years after dissident leader <PERSON> Benigno </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> was killed, the slaying remains unsolved and his goal of a peaceful, stable democracy unfulfilled in the turbulent country now governed by his widow. On Aug. 21, 1983, the senator stepped from a <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> jet and into Philippine history, gunned down moments after returning from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to challenge President <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> for leadership of the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. The killing outraged the nation and emboldened a fragmented opposition, paving the way for the uprising that toppled <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> and propelled <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> to the presidency on Feb. 25, 1986. Now, statues of `` Ninoy,'' the senator's nickname, stand in major cities, and the airport where he died bears his name. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> has said repeatedly that if it were not for his death, she never would have risen to power. But the trial of 40 defendants charged in the assassination drags on nearly 16 months after it began, bogged down in a complex legal system. In September 1986, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> voided acquittals handed down by a Marcos-era tribunal and ordered a retrial. The slow pace of the trial typifies the unfinished agenda of an administration made possible by the Aquino slaying. The political turbulence that made such a killing possible haunts the country. For many, the lofty hopes that <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' ouster alone would restore stability and prosperity have given way to frustration. `` Five years after <PERSON> Ninoy </PERSON>'s death, the <PERSON> Cory </PERSON> government has become the government it warned us against,'' wrote columnist <PERSON> Conrado </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Quiros </PERSON> in the <ORGANIZATION> Philippine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Globe </ORGANIZATION>, a frequent critic of the administration. Critics in the freewheeling <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> press often ignore Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s accomplishments, preferring instead to hold her to the idealistic promises of justice, domestic peace and social reform she espoused. Despite the insurgency and right-wing coup plots, her administration drafted a new constitution, restored a bicameral legislature and held national and regional elections in its first two years. The administration reversed three years of economic decline and posted a 5.5 percent growth in the gross national product in its first full year. But for millions of Filipinos, more than 60 percent of whom live in poverty, the slow pace of change has done little to improve their daily lives. Inflation in the <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> area, triggered by increases in prices of food and fuel, is approaching 10 percent. Allegations of continuing corruption have been raised not only by the press but by <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> Archbishop <PERSON> Cardinal </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaime </PERSON> <PERSON> Sin </PERSON>, the country's best known cleric and an Aquino supporter. Communist rebels still wield power in rural areas, and urban guerrillas have escalated street assassinations in the capital itself. Right-wing `` death squads'' have retaliated with their own attacks against labor activists and suspected leftists. `` If the principal element of -LRB- <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s -RRB- death was violence, it is only fitting that the people who were shocked by the incident and who felt sorry for the late senator should now shun violence and work to strengthen the rule of law,'' said The <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> Bulletin in an editorial Sunday. `` Violence still stalks the land, because many do not respect the rule of law.'' Growing disaffection prompted Vice President <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Laurel </LOCATION> this month to accuse the administration of incompetence, failing to stem the rebellion and tolerating corruption on the scale of <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>. Laurel called on Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> to resign and call new elections. Although Laurel's allegations were similar to those of some of Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s supporters, his charges won little public support, mostly because of the vice president's reputation as a political opportunist. `` But if -LRB- Laurel's -RRB- purpose was to jolt <PERSON> Cory </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> into waking up from her dream presidency and facing the nightmare it has become for the Filipino people, then it certainly deserves a fair and just assessment,'' wrote columnist <PERSON> Nestor </PERSON> <PERSON> Mata </PERSON> in The <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> Standard. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s strongest supporters frequently dismiss criticism as attempts by her opponents to undermine her government. Pro-Aquino columnists claim the latest round of criticism is part of a right-wing plot to tarnish her reputation among the public. `` Under the Aquino regime, blame is immediately being heaped on faceless, nameless people who are ` out to destabilize the government,''' wrote columnist <PERSON> Ninez </PERSON> <PERSON> Cacho-Olivarez </PERSON> in the Philippine Daily Inquirer. `` It is the insecure and paranoid who see goblins at every turn.'' Meanwhile, Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> herself has become more isolated from the Philippine press. She rarely gives press conferences or interviews. Recently, the presidential palace banned `` ambush interviews,'' where reporters would shout questions at the president as she walked to her office every morning.
