<SECOND>AM-Third World Roads,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Third World Needs $90 Billion for Roads, Report Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Third World countries need $ 43 billion worth of repairs to their roads, including many of their key thoroughfares, because over the last decade they failed to spend $ 12 billion or less to maintain them, the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> says in a report. The largest sum _ $ 11 billion _ is needed in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>, followed by $ 9.3 billion in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>, and another $ 9.3 billion in the poorer countries of the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The bank's experts said they were talking about a third of all paved roads outside of towns and a quarter of the unpaved roads in 85 countries. They found that 40 percent of the paved roads will need repair in the next 10 years, at a cost of another $ 40 billion. In 1984, the most recent year for which the report gives figures, the countries concerned put out $ 6.5 billion for repair and maintenance. `` But if these countries do not improve the management of roads, the eventual cost of restoration could easily increase two - to threefold, and the cost to users could rise even more,'' the report warned <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, owned by 151 countries, is the biggest single source of loans to help poor countries raise their living standards. It has lent about $ 15.5 billion for roads since it was founded at the end of World War II. Routine maintenance can cost as little as $ 480 a mile, while rebuilding can cost more than $ 480,000 a mile, the report said. The experts found the hard core of the problem in southern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. They took 61 Third World countries all over the world and found that 16 of