ch operates more than 700 pubs in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. The British <ORGANIZATION> Tourist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> expects 50,000 new jobs will be created in pubs and the catering trade. The <PERSON> Sherlock </PERSON> <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON> pub near <LOCATION> Trafalgar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> plans to serve full cream teas _ scones, <LOCATION> strawberry </LOCATION> <LOCATION> jam </LOCATION>, the works _ every afternoon. `` As far as I can see, the house -LRB- pub -RRB- will be more of a coffee shop in the afternoon than a drinking house,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, who manages the pub with his wife, <PERSON> Jean </PERSON>. `` I do n't think the average British person, after the initial shock, is going to be affected. It's more of a touristy thing.'' Only those pubs in busy tourist or commercial areas are expected to take advantage of the new hours, while those in residential areas will continue to close in the afternoon. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Licensed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Managers </ORGANIZATION>, which represents 13,000 pub managers, had feared increased overhead costs would push up beer prices if all pubs had to open in the afternoon. Beer prices have risen three to four pence -LRB- 5 cents -RRB- recently, but the breweries insist it's not because of the new hours. The going price for a pint of beer is 85 pence -LRB- $ 1.50 -RRB-.
