<FIRST>u a AM-Eliana-AIDS Bjt   08-21 0716</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eliana-AIDS, Bjt,0739</SECOND>
<HEAD>Adoptive Mother: Disappointed Over `Glass Cage,' Will Continue
Fight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT LEISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A mother who won a two-year fight to enroll her 6-year-old AIDS-afflicted daughter in school finds her victory bittersweet. `` This is the closest <PERSON> Eliana </PERSON> has been to a classroom. But I ca n't send her to school to sit in a cage,'' <PERSON> Rosa </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> said. The 36-year-old licensed practical nurse has struggled to give her daughter, who weighed 10 pounds when she was adopted at about 11 months, a home and medical care. Now she's fighting for an education for <PERSON> Eliana </PERSON>. Mrs. <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> is appealing a ruling by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Kovachevich </PERSON> allowing <PERSON> Eliana </PERSON> to start school Aug. 29, provided she remains behind a glass partition, isolated from other children in the classroom. Her attorney expects it to become a landmark case. `` The issues in this case involve critically important national policy,'' said <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanlon </PERSON>, who is taking the case to the 11th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. `` It's going to have long-lasting precedential effects.'' Ms. <PERSON> Kovachevich </PERSON> ruled that <PERSON> Eliana </PERSON>, who is retarded, may attend <ORGANIZATION> Manhattan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exceptional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, a school for disabled children. But the judge spelled out restrictions. In the classroom, <PERSON> Eliana </PERSON> must stay isolated inside a specially built glass booth until she is toilet-trained and stops sucking her fingers. Other children may play with her only if their parents sign consent forms. The enclosure, located toward the back of the room, must be 8-by-10 feet with a large plexiglass window and sound system. It's to have a toilet and desk An aide would be assigned to <PERSON> Eliana </PERSON> full time. <LOCATION> Hillsborough </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> school officials fought attempts to admit <PERSON> Eliana </PERSON> to the classroom. They feared she might transmit to others the acquired immune deficiency syndrome virus through bodily fluids. However, the judge wrote, no AIDS cases have been proved to have been transmitted through exposure to urine, feces or saliva even though the virus that causes the disease has been found in these bodily secretions. AIDS, according to the federal <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>, is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products, and from pregnant women to their offspring. For the past year, a teacher has come to <PERSON> Eliana </PERSON>'s home an hour a day; school officials wanted to continue that method of instruction. But Mrs. <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hanlon </PERSON> insisted that <PERSON> Eliana </PERSON> needed to be with other children. In her Aug. 8 ruling, Ms. <PERSON> Kovachevich </PERSON> said she was trying to address the concerns of both sides. Even though Mrs. <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> says she wo n't send <PERSON> Eliana </PERSON> to school next week, school officials are building an $ 8,000 glass enclosure. The plumbing is already finished. When Mrs. <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> first heard the judge's ruling she started to cry. `` I was angry and confused,'' she said in an interview last week. `` I said to myself, ` There's no way I'm going to do that, see her behind a cage watching other children and wanting to get out and play with them.' Then there was the confusion, the fear. I thought is this the only way we're going to be able to do it?'' <PERSON> Hanlon </PERSON> quoted pediatric and psychological experts as saying the classroom restrictions would be harmful to <PERSON> Eliana </PERSON> and could put even more stress on her weak immune system. <PERSON> Hillsborough </PERSON> school board member and former teacher <PERSON> Marion </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodgers </PERSON> called the booth `` cruel.'' `` If we did this in any other school setting for any other reason, the courts would have us there for child abuse,'' she said. Mrs. <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> adopted <PERSON> Eliana </PERSON> after she responded to a radio appeal in <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> for a baby living at a hospital. Doctors believe that <PERSON> Eliana </PERSON>, born prematurely, was exposed to AIDS when she had multiple transfusions as an infant. She has been on the AIDS-fighting drug AZT for the past year and her mother says she has improved noticeably over the last several months. The child's homebound teacher confirms that. `` She was deprived of family and we became that. She was deprived of health and we gave her the best medical attention we could,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> says. `` Now, I do n't want her deprived of an education. She needs more than an hour a week to progress. And she needs friends.''
