<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Apartheid,0566</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Seeks To Strengthen Residential Segregation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> JOHANNESBURG </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> _ The government plans to push ahead with tough new measures that would strengthen residential segregation, despite critics who say the proposals are `` straight out of the darkest ages of apartheid.'' Members of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> meet Monday in <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION> to debate a bill aimed at tightening enforcement of the Group Areas Act, which segregates all neighborhoods by race. Black activists, white businessmen and even the pro-government newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Beeld </ORGANIZATION> have condemned the measure, saying it entrenches apartheid and would force the evictions of thousands of blacks living peacefully, but illegally, in `` whites only'' areas. The proposed Group Areas Amendment Bill would make it easier to confiscate property and to evict and prosecute people living in areas not designated for their race group. `` It is a wicked, wicked, bill,'' said <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlisle </PERSON> of the anti-apartheid <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. `` It will drive decent people out of their homes.'' The bill calls for hiring inspectors to check for violations of the law. The maximum fine for property owners who allow a person to live outside his group area would increase from about $ 165 to $ 4,100. The maximum prison sentence would be increased from two years to five years. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has a surplus of housing in white neighborhoods, but a severe shortage in black areas. Thousands of non-whites have been moving into white areas such as <LOCATION> Hillbrow </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Woodstock </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION> in recent years. The government has not strictly enforced the 35-year-old Group Areas Act, angering conservative whites opposed to integrated neighborhoods. The issue of segregated neighborhoods is one of the hottest topics in the campaign for nationwide municipal elections Oct. 26, and the bill is seen as an accommodation to right-wing whites. President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> said last week he believes segregated housing is favored by 80 percent of whites, 70 percent of Asians and people of mixed race and a majority of blacks. `` It is rubbish to say 70 percent of our people would support the -LRB- Group Areas -RRB- Act,'' said <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Hendrickse </PERSON>, leader of the mixed-race chamber of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>. `` Mr. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> is this country's most dangerous liability It is about time he stepped down to make way for a person of greater vision and perception.'' Lawmakers also will address legislation that would allow creation of the first legal multiracial neighborhoods. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> would have veto power over any plans to create such `` open area.'' Other housing-related bills on the agenda seek to toughen existing laws against black slum areas and squatter settlements. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has as many as 7 million squatters among its 35 million population, according to some estimates. `` <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> is confronted by ... bills straight out of the darkest ages of apartheid,'' said the independent Sunday Times, the country's largest Sunday newspaper. `` Authorities will be armed with powers to summarily evict thousands, perhaps millions of people,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Sunday </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> said in a front-page editorial. `` Why must the legal process be distorted, property seized, witch hunters licensed and countless people be rendered homeless?'' By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
