<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Judges in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s traffic court system are pressured to maintain high conviction rates and to give police officers special guidance to make successful cases, a newspaper reported Sunday. The system, run by the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vehicles </ORGANIZATION>, operates `` in a fashion that is unfair, both in face and appearance, to the average motorist,'' according to an 11-month investigation conducted by the state <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> and obtained by the <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>. `` Cases are not necessarily decided on the facts, but rather on a preconceived idea of how many should be guilty,'' said <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> Jason </PERSON>, the former state <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> judge who led the inquiry. Among the findings of the study were that administrative law judges are pressed to be tough on motorists and to give police officers preferential treatment. The deputy commissioner of the <ORGANIZATION> motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> vehicles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> department </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheridan </PERSON>, told the newspaper that the bar association report `` completely distorted the record.'' `` Bits and pieces of information were put together and they leaped to conclusions not supported by the record and not supported by a fair and competent review of the system,'' he said. The bar association report said supervisors pressure judges to set higher fines and increase convictions. In addition, <ORGANIZATION> DMV </ORGANIZATION> officials track the percentage of guilty and innocent verdicts and average fines, and judges are required to review their monthl