<DATELINE>SALEM, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Oregon will add a section to state death certificates next year asking doctors to comment on the role tobacco played in the deaths of their patients. <PERSON> Joyce </PERSON> <PERSON> Grant-Worley </PERSON>, the state Health Division's chief research analyst, said last week that the 1989 death certificates will ask, `` Did tobacco use contribute to the death?'' Doctors will be able to check boxes marked `` yes,'' `` no,'' `` probably'' or `` unknown.'' <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> is the first state in the nation to add such a section to its death certificates, <PERSON> Grant-Worley </PERSON> said. The information will be used in ongoing studies of the link between smoking and death rates, she said. Oregon's research began in 1987, and while doctors were encouraged to report smoking-related deaths, the state provided no reminder on the forms. In the past, the state sent letters to doctors asking about tobacco use if lung cancer, emphysema, bronchitis or heart disease were reported on the death certificate without mention of smoking. `` We know that cigarette smoking kills,'' said <PERSON> Bonny </PERSON> <PERSON> Groshong </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>. `` Maybe this will give us stronger ammunition to take to the public to convince them.'' Health Division statistics gathered since 1987 from the voluntary participation of doctors indicate that tobacco use contributed to 70 percent to 82 percent of respiratory disease deaths in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>. Before 1987, smoking was listed on fewer than 5 percent of the death certificates that listed the respiratory diseases as the cause of death. Researchers say the deaths of about one in seven men and one in 10 women in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> were caused by lung cancer or other respiratory diseases in 1987. State health officials hope the statistics eventually will help lawmakers and health groups to plan programs to cut the smoking rate and identify those at risk for respiratory diseases. `` They'll probably find that cigarettes are responsible for a tremendous number of deaths in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>,'' said Dr. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Parosa </PERSON>, a Salem lung specialist. Oregon has one of the highest rates of respiratory disease in the nation. The state's 1987 lung cancer death rate was 59.7 per 100,000 population _ 9.1 percent higher than the estimated national rate.
