<HEAD>Thousads March On Anniversary of 1968 Invasion</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to move up reference to police response
and UPDATE with reports of tear gas, dogs used against some
demonstrators; picks up 14th graf pvs: Dvorak said...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Riot squads broke up a protest that began when 10,000 people marched through the capital Sunday to mark the 20th anniversary of the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact invasion that crushed the reforms of 1968. Baton-swinging police fired tear gas and charged the protesters with dogs about two hours after a chanting, clapping crowd began marching through the city. The march had dwindled to about 1,000 people when police moved in, beating at least two people and dragging others away. Waving Czechoslovak flags, the crowd began a march in <LOCATION> Wenceslas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> after a rally where hundreds signed a petition calling for democracy, human rights, the abolition of censorship and the withdrawal of Soviet troops. Many chanted the name of <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON>, who as <ORGANIZATION> Czechoslovak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader instituted the `` <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> Spring'' reforms before Soviet-led troops invaded on Aug. 20-21, 1968. At least five people were detained at different sites Sunday, including prominent activist Jan Urban. It was not known if Urban, a member of a human rights group called Charter 77, was released. The crowd that left Wenceslas square was joined by thousands of onlookers and the march swelled to about 10,000. Police made no move to disperse the crowd until it had thinned and protesters tried to return to the square. Police charged and dispersed the crowd, but no reports of injuries were available. Reporters saw helmeted police beating at least two people and two others were dragged away after shouting `` Dubcek'' and `` Freedom.'' The official <ORGANIZATION> CTK </ORGANIZATION> news agency said in a brief dispatch that `` groups of people attempted disturbing actions'' in Wenceslas Square. It was `` peaceful at the beginning. More prounounced attempts at provocation were recorded ... after the crowd moved to the <LOCATION> Old </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> and during a march through the streets of <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>,'' <ORGANIZATION> CTK </ORGANIZATION> said. ` The considerate and decisive action of the police prevented riots.'' In <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, an estimated 500 demonstrators gathered in a central park. When they began chanting `` <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>,'' police charged and dispersed the crowd. Several dozen people were taken away but the number of arrests was not known. About 100 demonstrators staged a second rally along <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s Arbat shopping mall, said <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Chuyev </PERSON>, a member of an unsanctioned political party called the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> He said police arrested an unspecified number of protesters. Before the march in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>, a group calling itself Independent Peace Initiative earlier met in <LOCATION> Wenceslas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> and drew up a 10-point petition. Peace campaigner <PERSON> Tomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Dvorak </PERSON> read it as hundreds loudly applauded each point. <PERSON> Dvorak </PERSON> said the petition would be sent to Czechoslovak state, government and party leaders and the state-run media. At one point, a policeman passed through the tightly packed crowd and grabbed copies of the signed petitions. The crowd jeered and yelled `` Shame.'' Reporters saw police spraying mace into the face of at least one citizen. Earlier on <LOCATION> Wenceslas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>, 200 people walked behind two representatives of the Charter 77 movement, <PERSON> Eva </PERSON> <PERSON> Kanturkova </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Hradilek </PERSON>, who tried to lay flowers by the statue of King Wenceslas. Uniformed police pushed back the two activis