rchase offer would approach the $ 26-a-share level. `` I do n't see how anybody could pay that much,'' he said. Analysts note that the biggest profits in the pharmaceutical industry come from companies that produce new products; <PERSON> Scherer </PERSON> is engaged only in packaging. `` I think it is a fine company in and of itself, but as a possible acquisition for a drug company or chemical company, it does n't make sense,'' he said. Mrs. <PERSON> Fink </PERSON>, supported by her brother, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Scherer </PERSON>, thinks this is an opportune time to sell the company because there is no guarantee <PERSON> Scherer </PERSON>'s recent record annual sales of $ 290.7 million and earnings of $ 15.1 million will continue. `` <PERSON> John </PERSON> and I watched our father build this company. He made our mother and their children partners in it nearly 50 years ago ... and I believe he would have heartily endorsed a sale,'' she said. Mrs. <PERSON> Fink </PERSON> and her brother control about 38 percent of the company. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Fink </PERSON>, <PERSON> Scherer </PERSON>'s president and chief executives officer, said there have been no offers and stressed that shareholders would profit most if the company remained independent. He said he is trying to prevent the dispute from becoming a distraction for <PERSON> Scherer </PERSON>'s 2,800 employees. `` I'd rather not refer to them as damage control measures,'' he said after last week's stockholder meeting. `` We've tried to contain the diversion to as few people as possible.'' Some stockholders say the company will be damaged whatever the outcome the family dispute, which saw Mrs. <PERSON> Fink </PERSON> file for divorce weeks after the board rejected her sale proposal. `` What we are really witnessing here is the wounding of a unique and special company,'' <PERSON> Hudson </PERSON> told about 200 people at last week's meeting Mrs. <PERSON> Fink </PERSON> says she just wants what is best for stockholders. Four months ago Mrs. <PERSON> Fink </PERSON> rejected a suggestion by some directors that the company pay a one-time dividend that would benefit her and her brother, in return for reducing their voting power. `` I think that's the kind of deal I'd try to cut right now,'' <PERSON> Gulis </PERSON> said.
