<HEAD>Borscht Belt Image Downplayed As Catskill Resorts Attempt
Revitalization</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Margo Jones ...' to include beet in recipe.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTICELLO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> state's venerable <LOCATION> Catskill </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> resorts, once known collectively as the `` borscht belt'' because of their ethnic flavor and abundance of food, are trying to update their image. These days, some resorts are trying to be part of the `` sushi belt.'' Tourism officials distribute brochures in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> praising the region's golf courses. The tables at the golf clubhouse of the Concord Hotel, the region's largest, have buffet menus printed in both English and Japanese. It's just one indication of how times are changing for the region, whose old ways were popularized in the romantic movie `` Dirty Dancing.'' <PERSON> Margo </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> does n't cringe at the mention of borscht, the beet and cabbage soup popular at the predominantly Jewish hotels, but <LOCATION> Sullivan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>'s publicity director quickly steers the conversation to a new nickname _ CatskilLand. The name, she said, is meant to convey the Catskills' more active image as a center for sports and recreation. `` I do n't think we'll ever get away from that ethnic image and I do n't think we want to,'' <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said. `` Some of the things we like about the image are the sense of tradition, a sense of family and a warmth that you do n't get from a chain hotel.'' <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> Kutsher </PERSON>, for example, still prowls around the huge resort in <LOCATION> Monticello </LOCATION> his family has run since 1907. Nevertheless, many of the 500 resorts that once dotted the area have folded or converted to other uses; about a dozen giants now handle the bulk of the visitors. Like many resort areas close to big cities, the <LOCATION> Catskills </LOCATION> _ about a two-hour ride from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> _ began to fade as a tourist destination in recent years. Air travel made other resorts, both in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> and overseas _ more accessible. The summertime routine of large meals broken up by an occasional game of `` Simon Says'' was also less appealing to newer generations of Catskills visitors. Even the hotels' nightclubs, which gave birth to dozens of <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> careers, did n't seem so attractive anymore. It was a case of adapt or die, and the Catskills did a better job than areas like the <LOCATION> Adirondack </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION> in upstate <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, travel industry analyst for the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION>. `` To some extent, the times are changing back toward the <LOCATION> Catskills </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> said. `` You have a rise in dual working couples. That segment has money, but what they do n't have is time. More likely a two-career couple wants to take three days off and go someplace nearby and relax and have a lot of activities there.'' That's why `` CatskilLand's'' color brochure shows a young couple whacking a tennis ball, dipping into a swimming pool and hitting a golf ball. Skiiers and other weekend athletes are most welcome. Resort owners continue to use their imaginations to draw guests. <PERSON> Grossinger </PERSON>'s hosted the first `` singles only'' weekend back in 1962; a concept updated with an'80s twist at the <LOCATION> Concord </LOCATION> resort, which publishes its own newsletter with personal advertisements. Hotels also have recently sponsored special weekends for single parents and for infertile couples, <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said. The Catskills' crowds also are n't as predictable as they used to be. The families who still come to the Catskills for their bar mitzvahs now room side by side with corporate executives on retreats or training seminars, <PERSON> Kutsher </PERSON> said. At <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> travel shows, <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said she's known as `` the golf lady'' among Japanese tourists who enjoy the relatively uncrowded Catskills links. Many of the large hotels are also expanding their services to include condominiums offered for use by time-sharing vacationers. While the Catskills can claim a revival _ <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said her office had 101,000 inquiries from tourists in 1986 compared to 24,000 in 1980 _ it ca n't say the comeback is complete. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>'s Hotel, one of the top resorts, filed for bankruptcy last month, although the hotel remains open. <PERSON> Grossinger </PERSON>'s, once the king of the Catskills, has been closed since 1986, although its new owners promise a remodeled resort will debut in 1989. `` It hurt us a lot individually because we were friends with these people,'' <PERSON> Kutsher </PERSON> said of <PERSON> Grossinger </PERSON>'s closing. `` But <PERSON> Grossinger </PERSON>'s will rise out of the ashes.'' If it does, its new owners hope it will typify the new Catskills. The newly named <PERSON> Grossinger </PERSON>'s Resort and <ORGANIZATION> Spa </ORGANIZATION> will contain some non-kosher restaurants and townhouses, said <PERSON> Bernie </PERSON> <PERSON> Roth </PERSON>, the resort's general manager.
