<FIRST>r f AM-DropoutCampaign Bjt   08-21 0889</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dropout Campaign, Bjt,0921</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ashland Oil Will Be Anonymous Sponsor In Campaign Against Dropout
Problem</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. HACKETT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> spends millions of dollars to improve education in this country, but the company's name will be missing from the latest attack on the high school dropout problem A series of 30-second television and radio spots and newspaper and magazine ads will be released nationwide this week and be identified as public-service announcements from two not-for-profit organizations: the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governments </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION> and the Advertising Council in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> donated materials and services for the ads but chose to remove its name from them, remain anonymous and give credit to the two not-for profit groups _ an action described as unique and unprecedented by both councils and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dropout </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prevention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Clemson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` It is an excellent public awareness program about the dropout crisis in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Smink </PERSON>, the center's executive director. `` When more parents, communities and corporations learn about the potential we are losing, we are more likely to get them involved in projects to keep youngsters in school,'' <PERSON> Smink </PERSON> said. The goal of the campaign _ to be kicked off Monday at a <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION> news conference _ is to help reduce government statistics showing that 682,000 students _ an average of 3,789 daily _ disappeared from their classrooms during the 1985-86 school year. `` The figures staggered us, and we decided to expand a program that we've had in place about a year,'' said <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Lacy </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION>'s vice president for corporate communications <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> had previously launched an anti-dropout campaign in <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, using all media to emphasize the importance of a high school diploma. Educators in both states reported the campaign had an impact on youngsters who saw the advertising. The idea was n't new for <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION>, which has distributed at least $ 10 million in the past five years in scholarships and college endowments. The total does not include money spent in other fields of education by <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION>. `` We approached the Advertising Council ... and asked if it would be interested in running the program nationally, like the ones it did on Smokey the Bear and drinking and driving,'' <PERSON> Lacy </PERSON> said. There was one hitch. `` The council must have a non-profit organization as a sponsor,'' <PERSON> Lacy </PERSON> explained. But Ashland found one in the Council of State Governments. All material that <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> had used in its two-state drive was donated to Doe-Anderson Advertising of <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION> for use in the national campaign. The agency's services also were donated. `` Our logo was stripped from the advertisements and replaced with that of the two councils,'' said <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wiley </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION>'s director of advertising and communications One of two tapes going to television stations depicts a depressed youngster sitting in a corner of his garage. A few feet away, an expensive sports car rests on cinder blocks. The narrator explains that `` two years ago, this car was the most important thing in <PERSON> Joey </PERSON>'s life. He spent every spare dime he had on it. He even quit high school to get a job so he could have the hottest ride in town. `` Today, the job is gone,'' the narrator continues. `` The car does n't work anymore and, without a high school diploma, neither does <PERSON> Joey </PERSON>. `` Winners never quit. Stay in school,'' the ad concludes. The second tape depicts a teen-age mother clutching an infant. She tells the audience: `` Making ends meet has n't been easy with three of us at home. Jobs are pretty scarce around here, especially since neither my husband nor me finished school. `` But it's going to be different for this one. He's going to stay in high school if I have to tie him to his chair. Sometimes, I wish someone had done me that way.'' The tape ends with this plea: `` Stay in school. Someone's future could depend on it.'' <PERSON> Wiley </PERSON> estimated it will cost <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> about $ 50,000 for mailing the ads to the media. `` The packages will contain a brief summary of how the project came about, but this is the only recognition we will receive.'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamby </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dropout </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prevention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>'s assistant director, said, `` There are many, many reasons why kids give up on education. Any project that attempts to keep them from becoming a statistic has to be a plus.'' <PERSON> Hamby </PERSON> said studies have shown many girls cite pregnancy and marriage as their reasons for abandoning education plans while boys tend to blame their dislike for school. Both groups also mention economic reasons, <PERSON> Hamby </PERSON> said. Dropout rates are higher among single-parent and lower-income families, he added. <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>'s dropout rate has been declining, and <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION>'s commercials, which began in August 1987, have been a factor, said Dr. <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>, director of pupil attendance in the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> In the 1983-84 school year, there were 14,224 dropouts in <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, but that number shrank to 9,633 for 1986-87. `` Those commercials have to get part of the credit,'' <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said. Businessmen who saw the ads came up with suggestions to help dropouts, and <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> now has more residents going into the General Education Diploma program than in past years, <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said. `` And for the first time in our history, people are passing in greater numbers than those who are quitting school,'' he said.
</TEXT>
