<HEAD>Armtek Reports Negotiations with Third Party</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Armtek </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which has rejected a $ 550 million buyout offer from <ORGANIZATION> Mark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> IV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, says it is negotiating with a third party interested in buying the plastics and chemicals company. The announcement Friday came one day after Mark IV sweetened its offer for all of <ORGANIZATION> Armtek </ORGANIZATION>'s stock to $ 44 a share from its original $ 40-a-share bid. Armtek's board, which rejected <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> IV </PERSON>'s original share as inadequate, has not responded to the latest offer. The company said it informed the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> that negotiations with the third party `` may be dependent upon future actions of Mark IV Industries with respect to the amended offer.'' Armtek earlier said it would consider a third-party acquisition, and in its <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> filing, the company said it was also considering recapitalization proposals. Investors apparently expect bidding for Armtek to continue. The company's stock rose $ 1 a share to $ 46.50 in <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> trading Friday. Armtek is facing four class action suits in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, where it is incorporated, from shareholders who charge the company's directors are trying to thwart the Mark IV takeover attempt and have n't satisfactorily explored the offer One suit claims <ORGANIZATION> Armtek </ORGANIZATION>'s directors have `` embarked upon a course of action designed to entrench themselves in the management and control of <LOCATION> Armtek </LOCATION> and to protect and enhance their personal financial benefits'' at the expense of shareholders. Armtek, formerly known as <ORGANIZATION> Armstrong </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rubber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, is a supplier of engineered drive and heat exchange systems, modules and components and specialty polymers. It had $ 1.2 billion in sales last year. Two month ago, <ORGANIZATION> Armtek </ORGANIZATION> sold its largest unit, <ORGANIZATION> Armstrong </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, to the Italian tire maker <ORGANIZATION> Pirelli </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> for $ 197 million, capping a corporate restructuring. Mark IV, based in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Amherst </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, produces professional audio, technical and aerospace products. The company had 1987 sales of $ 292 million.
