<FIRST>r f AM-Iran-Oil     08-21 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Oil,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Plans to Repair Oil Facilities Hit In War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> will repair vital oil facilities battered in the war with <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> at `` maximum speed'' as soon as the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> Nation-sponsored cease-fire proves to be durable, Oil Minister <PERSON> Golamreza </PERSON> <PERSON> Aqazadeh </PERSON> says. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s official <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, monitored in <LOCATION> Nicosia </LOCATION>, quoted <PERSON> Aqazadeh </PERSON> as saying Saturday <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> will also go ahead with major oil industry projects to boost exports, refining capacity and exploration and expand its energy industry. Rebuilding its oil industry, particularly its seven existing refineries which were badly hit, is one of <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>'s top priorities now that the shooting has stopped. <PERSON> Aqazadeh </PERSON> said the Iranians want to bolster oil exports as quickly as possible to fund the massive task of reconstruction. Before the cease-fire, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s government had projected oil earnings of around $ 9 billion for this year. But weak oil prices were expected to reduce that figure. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> is currently producing around 2.3 million barrels of oil a day, the output quota set by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries. Its current export level is an estimated 1.7 million barrels a day, despite <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> efforts to choke <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>'s economic lifeline. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s powerful air force concentrated much of its bombing offensive on <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s oil facilities and tankers during the 8-year-old war. <PERSON> Aqazadeh </PERSON> said a new oil loading terminal at <LOCATION> Gavaneh </LOCATION> in the northern end of the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> began operations soon after the gulf war cease-fire took effect Saturday. <PERSON> Aqazadeh </PERSON> said the big refinery at <LOCATION> Abadan </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Khuzestan </LOCATION> province, put out of action early in the war, will be rebuilt and expanded into `` one of the most sophisticated refineries of its kind.'' The refinery, with a capacity of 630,000 barrels a day, was the biggest in the world before it was knocked out by the Iraqis. The minister said another major refinery at <LOCATION> Isfahan </LOCATION> was now operating at its pre-war capacity of around 200,000 barrels a day after being bombed 15 times during the conflict. He did not mention the other refineries that were bombed. Earlier this year, Western experts estimated that <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s overall refinery capacity of 700,000 barrels a day had been reduced by more than one-third because of war damage. That forced the Iranians to import unprecedented amounts of refined products, such as aviation fuel and kerosene, from abroad. <PERSON> Aqazadeh </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> will push ahead with plans to build a new oil refinery with a capacity of 220,000 barrels a day and a $ 1.5 billion petrochemical complex at the western city of <LOCATION> Arak </LOCATION>. The Iranians have also announced plans to build two other smaller refineries in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> and the port of <PERSON> Taheri </PERSON>, midway down the gulf near offshore oil and gas fields.
</TEXT>
</DOC>